    <div class=3D"bar pure-g">
      <h1 class=3D"pure-u-1 pure-u-md-4-5">
        <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-jepsen-cassandra">Jepsen: Ca=
ssandra</a>
      </h1>

      <div class=3D"meta pure-u-1 pure-u-md-1-5">
        <div class=3D"tags"><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/tags/software">Sof=
tware</a> <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/tags/network">Network</a> <a href=3D=
"https://aphyr.com/tags/distributed-systems">Distributed Systems</a> <a hre=
f=3D"https://aphyr.com/tags/jepsen">Jepsen</a> <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com=
/tags/cassandra">Cassandra</a></div>
        <time datetime=3D"Sep 24, 2013, 10:32:06 PM" pubdate=3D"">
          2013-09-24
        </time>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class=3D"body">
      <p><em>Previously on <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/tags/jepsen">Jepsen=
</a>, we learned about <a href=3D"http://aphyr.com/posts/293-call-me-maybe-=
kafka">Kafka=E2=80=99s proposed replication design</a>.</em></p>
<p>Cassandra is a Dynamo system; like Riak, it divides a hash ring into a s=
everal chunks, and keeps N replicas of each chunk on different nodes. It us=
es tunable quorums, hinted handoff, and active anti-entropy to keep replica=
s up to date. Unlike the Dynamo paper and some of its peers, Cassandra esch=
ews vector clocks in favor of a pure last-write-wins approach.</p>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#some-wri=
te-loses" id=3D"some-write-loses">Some Write Loses</a></h2>
<p>If you read <a href=3D"http://aphyr.com/posts/285-call-me-maybe-riak">th=
e Riak article</a>, you might be freaking out at this point. In Riak, last-=
write-wins resulted in dropping 30-70% of writes, even with the strongest c=
onsistency settings (R=3DW=3DPR=3DPW=3DALL), even with a perfect lock servi=
ce ensuring writes did not occur simultaneously. To understand why, I=E2=80=
=99d like to briefly review the problem with last-write-wins in asynchronou=
s networks.</p>
<p></p><div class=3D"left"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https:=
//aphyr.com/data/posts/294/cassandra-lww-diagram.jpg" alt=3D"cassandra-lww-=
diagram.jpg" title=3D"cassandra-lww-diagram.jpg"></div><p></p>
<p>In this causality diagram, two clients (far left and far right) add the =
elements =E2=80=9Ca=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cb=E2=80=9D, and =E2=80=9Cc=E2=80=9D =
to a set stored in an LWW register (middle line). The left client adds a, w=
hich is read by both clients. One client adds b, constructing the set [a b]=
. The other adds c, constructing the set [a c]. Both write their values bac=
k. Because the register is last-write-wins, it preserves whichever arrives =
with the highest timestamp. In this case, it=E2=80=99s as if the write from=
 the client on the left <em>never even happened</em>. However, it could jus=
t as easily have discarded the write from the right-hand client. Without a =
strong external coordinator, there=E2=80=99s just no way to tell whose data=
 will be preserved, and whose will be thrown away.</p>
<p>Again: in an LWW register, the only conditions under which you can guara=
ntee your write will not be silently ignored are when the register=E2=80=99=
s value is <em>immutable</em>. If you never change the value, it doesn=E2=
=80=99t matter which copy you preserve.</p>
<p></p><div style=3D"clear: both"></div><p></p>
<p>Vector clocks avoid this problem by identifying conflicting writes, and =
allowing you to merge them together.</p>
<p><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/2=
94/cassandra-vclock-merge.jpg" alt=3D"cassandra-vclock-merge.jpg" title=3D"=
cassandra-vclock-merge.jpg"></p>
<p>Because there=E2=80=99s no well-defined order for potential conflicts, t=
he merge function needs to be associative, commutative, and idempotent. If =
it satisfies those three properties (in essence, if you can merge any value=
s in any order and get the same result), the system forms a <em>semilattice=
</em> known as a <a href=3D"http://pagesperso-systeme.lip6.fr/Marc.Shapiro/=
papers/RR-6956.pdf">CRDT</a>, and you recover a type of order-free consiste=
ncy known as <em>lattice consistency</em>. Last-write-wins is a particular =
type of CRDT=E2=80=93albeit, not a particularly good one, because it destro=
ys information nondeterministically.</p>
<p>Early in Cassandra=E2=80=99s history, Cassandra chose <em>not</em> to im=
plement vector clocks for performance reasons. Vclocks (typically) require =
a read before each write. By using last-write-wins in all cases, and ignori=
ng the causality graph, Cassandra can cut the number of round trips require=
d for a write from 2 to 1, and obtain a significant speedup. The downside i=
s that there is no safe way to modify a Cassandra cell.</p>
<p>Some people claim you <em>can</em> serialize updates to a cell by perfec=
tly synchronizing your clocks, using ConsistencyLevel.QUORUM or ALL, and us=
ing an external lock service to prevent simultaneous operations. Heck, the =
official Cassandra documentation even claims this:</p>
<p><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/2=
94/cassandra-cap.png" alt=3D"cassandra-cap.png" title=3D"cassandra-cap.png"=
></p>
<p><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/2=
94/cassandra-consistency.png" alt=3D"cassandra-consistency.png" title=3D"ca=
ssandra-consistency.png"></p>
<p>As we=E2=80=99ll see throughout this post, the Cassandra documentation c=
an be less than accurate. Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://github.com/ap=
hyr/jepsen/blob/master/src/jepsen/cassandra.clj#L35-L80">Jepsen test</a> wh=
ich mutates the same cell repeatedly, using perfectly synchronized clocks, =
QUORUM consistency, and a perfect lock service:</p>
<pre><code>$ lein run lock cassandra
...
Writes completed in 200.036 seconds

2000 total
1009 acknowledged
724 survivors
285 acknowledged writes lost! (=E2=95=AF=C2=B0=E2=96=A1=C2=B0=EF=BC=89=E2=
=95=AF=EF=B8=B5 =E2=94=BB=E2=94=81=E2=94=BB
1 3 6 8 11 13 ... 1986 1988 1991 1993 1996 1998
0.5045 ack rate
0.2824579 loss rate
0.0 unacknowledged but successful rate
</code></pre>
<p>Losing 28% of your supposedly committed data is not linearizable by any =
definition. Next question.</p>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#cql-and-=
crdts" id=3D"cql-and-crdts">CQL and CRDTs</a></h2>
<p>Without vector clocks, Cassandra can=E2=80=99t safely <em>change</em> a =
cell=E2=80=93but writing immutable data <em>is</em> safe. Consequently, Cas=
sandra has evolved around those constraints, allowing you to efficiently jo=
urnal thousands of cells to a single row, and to retrieve them in sorted or=
der. Instead of modifying a cell, you write each distinct change to its own=
 UUID-keyed cell. Then, at read time, you read all the cells back and apply=
 a merge function to obtain a result.</p>
<p></p><div class=3D"left"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https:=
//aphyr.com/data/posts/294/cassandra-immutable-oplog-2.jpg" alt=3D"cassandr=
a-immutable-oplog-2.jpg" title=3D"cassandra-immutable-oplog-2.jpg"></div><d=
iv class=3D"right"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.=
com/data/posts/294/cassandra-merge.jpg" alt=3D"cassandra-merge.jpg" title=
=3D"cassandra-merge.jpg"></div><div style=3D"clear: both"></div><p></p>
<p>Cassandra=E2=80=99s query language, CQL, provides some collection-orient=
ed data structures around this model: sets, lists, maps, and so forth. They=
=E2=80=99re CRDTs, though the semantics don=E2=80=99t align with what you=
=E2=80=99ll find in the INRIA paper=E2=80=93no G-sets, 2P-sets, OR-sets, et=
c. However, some operations <em>are</em> safe=E2=80=93for instance, <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/aphyr/jepsen/blob/master/src/jepsen/cassandra.clj#L1=
16-L149">adding elements to a CQL set</a>:</p>
<pre><code>0 unrecoverable timeouts
Collecting results.
Writes completed in 200.036 seconds

2000 total
2000 acknowledged
2000 survivors
All 2000 writes succeeded. :-D
</code></pre>
<p>That=E2=80=99s terrific! This is the same behavior we saw with G-sets in=
 Riak. However, not all CQL collection operations are intuitively correct. =
In particular, I=E2=80=99d be wary of the index-based operations for lists,=
 updating elements in a map, and <em>any</em> type of deletions. Deletes ar=
e implemented by writing special tombstone cells, which declare a range of =
other cells to be ignored. Because Cassandra <em>doesn=E2=80=99t</em> use t=
echniques like OR-sets, you can potentially delete records that haven=E2=80=
=99t been seen yet=E2=80=93even delete writes from the future. Cassandra us=
ers jokingly refer to this behavior as =E2=80=9Cdoomstones=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p>The important thing to remember is that because there are no ordering co=
nstraints on writes, one=E2=80=99s merge function must still be associative=
 and commutative. Just as we saw with Riak, AP systems require you to reaso=
n about <em>order-free</em> data structures. In fact, Cassandra and Riak ar=
e (almost) formally equivalent in their consistency semantics=E2=80=93the p=
rimary differences are in the granularity of updates, in garbage collection=
/history compaction, and in performance.</p>
<p>Bottom line: CQL collections are a great idea, and you should use them! =
Read the specs carefully to figure out whether CQL operations meet your nee=
ds, and if they don=E2=80=99t, you can always <a href=3D"http://www.slidesh=
are.net/rbranson/cassandra-at-instagram-aug-2013">write your own CRDTs on t=
op of wide rows</a> yourself.</p>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#counters=
" id=3D"counters">Counters</a></h2>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re familiar with CRDTs, you might be wondering whether Ca=
ssandra=E2=80=99s counter type is a PN-counter=E2=80=93a commutative, monot=
onic data structure which can be incremented and decremented in an eventual=
ly consistent way. The answer is no: Cassandra (via Twitter, politics, etc)=
, wound up with a less safe type of data structure. Consequently, Cassandra=
 counters will over- or under-count by a wide range during a network partit=
ion.</p>
<p>If partitioned for about half of the test run, I found counters could dr=
ift by up to 50% of the expected value. Here=E2=80=99s a relatively well-be=
haved run, drifting by less than a percent.</p>
<pre><code>10000 total
9700 acknowledged
9921 survivors
</code></pre>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#isolatio=
n" id=3D"isolation">Isolation</a></h2>
<p>In <a href=3D"http://www.datastax.com/dev/blog/row-level-isolation">Comi=
ng up in Cassandra 1.1: Row Level Isolation</a>, and <a href=3D"http://www.=
datastax.com/dev/blog/atomic-batches-in-cassandra-1-2">Atomic batches in Ca=
ssandra 1.2</a>, DataStax asserts that a write which updates multiple keys =
in the same row will be atomic and isolated.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Cassandra 1.1 guarantees that if you update both the login and the passw=
ord in the same update (for the same row key) then no concurrent read may s=
ee only a partial update.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And from <a href=3D"http://www.datastax.com/documentation/cassandra/1.2/=
webhelp/?pagename=3Ddocs&amp;version=3D1.2&amp;file=3D#cassandra/dml/dml_ab=
out_transactions_c.html">the official documentation on concurrency control<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Full row-level isolation is now in place so that writes to a row are iso=
lated to the client performing the
write and are not visible to any other user until they are complete.
From a transactional ACID (atomic, consistent, isolated, durable) standpoin=
t, this enhancement now gives
Cassandra transactional AID support.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>We know what =E2=80=9Catomic=E2=80=9D means: either all of the changes i=
n the transaction complete, or none of them do. But what does =E2=80=9Cisol=
ated=E2=80=9D mean? Isolated in the sense of ACID? Let=E2=80=99s ask Hacker=
 News what <em>they</em> think Cassandra=E2=80=99s isolation provides:</p>
<p><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/2=
94/isolation4.png" alt=3D"isolation4.png" title=3D"isolation4.png"><img cla=
ss=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/isolatio=
n5.png" alt=3D"isolation5.png" title=3D"isolation5.png"><img class=3D"attac=
hment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/isolation2.png" alt=
=3D"isolation2.png" title=3D"isolation2.png"><img class=3D"attachment pure-=
img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/isolation1.png" alt=3D"isolati=
on1.png" title=3D"isolation1.png"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D=
"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/isolation3.png" alt=3D"isolation3.png" ti=
tle=3D"isolation3.png"></p>
<p>Peter Bailis pointed me at two really <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/=
posts/294/adya-phd.pdf">excellent</a> papers on isolation and consistency, =
including Berenson et al=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/pdf/cs/0701=
157.pdf">A Critique of ANSI SQL Isolation Levels</a>=E2=80=93I really recom=
mend digging into them if you=E2=80=99re curious about this problem. Isolat=
ion comes in many flavors, or strengths, depending on what sorts of causal =
histories are allowed. Serializability is one of the strongest: all transac=
tions appear to occur in a single well-defined non-interleaved order. Curso=
r Stability (CS) and Snapshot Isolation (SI) are somewhat weaker.</p>
<p>ANSI SQL defines four levels of isolation, which really have more to do =
with the historical behavior of various database systems than with behavior=
 that any sane person would consider distinguishible, so I=E2=80=99m not go=
ing to get into the details=E2=80=93but suffice it to say that there are a =
range of <em>phenomena</em> which are prohibited by those isolation levels.=
 In order from least to most awful:</p>
<ul>
<li>P3: Phantom</li>
<li>P2: Fuzzy read</li>
<li>P1: Dirty read</li>
<li>P0: Dirty write</li>
</ul>
<p>ANSI SQL=E2=80=99s SERIALIZABLE level prohibits P3-P0; REPEATABLE READ p=
rohibits P2 and below, READ COMMITTED prohibits P1 and below, and READ UNCO=
MMITTED only prohibits P0.</p>
<p></p><div class=3D"right"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https=
://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/p0-example.jpg" alt=3D"p0-example.jpg" title=3D=
"p0-example.jpg"></div><p></p>
<p></p><div class=3D"right"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https=
://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/cassandra-comparison-diagram.jpg" alt=3D"cassan=
dra-comparison-diagram.jpg" title=3D"cassandra-comparison-diagram.jpg"></di=
v><p></p>
<p>P0, or =E2=80=9Cdirty write=E2=80=9D is especially important because <em=
>all</em> isolation levels must prohibit it. In P0, one transaction modifie=
s some data; then a second transaction <em>also</em> modifies that data, <e=
m>before</em> the first transaction commits. We <em>never</em> want writes =
from two different transactions to be mixed together, because it might viol=
ate integrity relationships which each transaction held independently. For =
instance, we might write [x=3D1, y=3D1] in one transaction, and [x=3D2, y=
=3D2] in a different transaction, assuming that x will always be equal to y=
. P0 allows those transactions to result in [x=3D1, y=3D2], or [x=3D2, y=3D=
1].</p>
<p>Cassandra allows P0.</p>
<p>The key thing to remember here is that in Cassandara, the order of write=
s is completely irrelevant. Any write made to the cluster could eventually =
wind up winning, if it has a higher timestamp. But=E2=80=93what happens if =
Cassandra sees two copies of a cell with the same timestamp?</p>
<p>It picks the lexicographically bigger <em>value</em>.</p>
<p>That means that if the values written to two distinct cells don=E2=80=99=
t have the same sort order (which is likely), Cassandra could pick final ce=
ll values from <em>different</em> transactions. For instance, we might writ=
e [1 -1] and [2 -2]. 2 is greater than 1, so the first cell will be 2. But =
-1 is bigger than -2, so -1 wins in the second cell. The result? [2 -1].</p=
>
<p>=E2=80=9CBut,=E2=80=9D you might protest, =E2=80=9CIn order for that to =
happen, you=E2=80=99d need two timestamps to collide. It=E2=80=99s really u=
nlikely that two writes will get the same microsecond-resolution timestamp,=
 right? I=E2=80=99ve never seen it happen in my cluster.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Well, it depends. If we assume N writes per second by Poisson processes =
to the same row, the probability of any given read seeing a conflicting val=
ue grows as the writes come closer together.</p>
<p></p><div class=3D"right"><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https=
://aphyr.com/data/posts/294/cassandra-ts-conflict-visible-chart.jpg" alt=3D=
"cassandra-ts-conflict-visible-chart.jpg" title=3D"cassandra-ts-conflict-vi=
sible-chart.jpg"></div><p></p>
<pre>rate    probability of conflict/read
------------------------------------
1       1.31E-7
10      5.74E-6
100     5.30E-5
1000    5.09E-4
10000   0.00504
100000  0.0492
1000000 0.417
</pre>
<p>So if you do 100,000 writes/sec, on any given read you=E2=80=99ve got a =
5% chance of seeing corrupt data. If you do 10 writes/sec and 1 read/sec, i=
n each day you=E2=80=99ve got about a 1/3 chance of seeing corrupt data in =
any given day.</p>
<p>What if you write <em>many</em> rows over time=E2=80=93maybe 2 writes to=
 each row, separated by a mean delta of 100 milliseconds? Then the theoreti=
cal probability of any given <em>row</em> being corrupt is about 5 =C3=97 1=
0^-6. That=E2=80=99s a pretty small probability=E2=80=93and remember, most =
applications can tolerate some small degree of corrupt data. Let=E2=80=99s =
confirm it with <a href=3D"https://github.com/aphyr/jepsen/blob/master/src/=
jepsen/cassandra.clj#L154-L226">an experiment</a>:</p>
<pre><code>10000 total
9899 acknowledged
9942 survivors
58 acknowledged writes lost! (=E2=95=AF=C2=B0=E2=96=A1=C2=B0=EF=BC=89=E2=95=
=AF=EF=B8=B5 =E2=94=BB=E2=94=81=E2=94=BB
127 253 277 339 423 434 ... 8112 8297 8650 8973 9096 9504
101 unacknowledged writes found! =E3=83=BD(=C2=B4=E3=83=BC=EF=BD=80)=E3=83=
=8E
1059 1102 1139 1142 1143 1158 ... 2701 2720 2721 2800 2815 2860
0.9899 ack rate
0.0058591776 loss rate
0.01020305 unacknowledged but successful rate
</code></pre>
<p>Note that =E2=80=9Cwrites lost=E2=80=9D here means corrupted rows: entir=
ely missing rows are treated as successes. Roughly 1 in 200 rows were corru=
pt! That=E2=80=99s <em>way</em> worse than 10^-6! What gives?</p>
<p>It turns out that <em>somewhere</em> in this maze of software, either Ca=
ssandra, the DataStax Java driver, or Cassaforte is taking the current time=
 in <em>milliseconds</em> and tacking on three zeroes to the end, calling i=
t good. The probability of millisecond conflicts is significantly higher th=
an microsecond conflicts, which is why we saw so much corrupt data.</p>
<p>Long story short, Cassandra row isolation is probabilistic at best; and =
remember, the only reason you actually <em>want</em> isolation is because y=
ou plan on doing two operations <em>at the same time</em>. If you rely on i=
solation, in <em>any</em> sense of the word, in Cassandra, you need to cons=
ider your tolerance for data corruption, and <em>verify</em> that you=E2=80=
=99re actually generating timestamps with the expected distribution. A stro=
ng external coordinator which guarantees unique timestamps might be of use.=
</p>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#lightwei=
ght-transactions" id=3D"lightweight-transactions">Lightweight Transactions<=
/a></h2>
<p>In Cassandra 2.0.0, Lightweight Transactions offer <a href=3D"http://www=
.datastax.com/dev/blog/lightweight-transactions-in-cassandra-2-0">lineariza=
ble consistency</a> for compare-and-set operations. The implementation is b=
ased on naive Paxos=E2=80=93requiring four round trips for each write=E2=80=
=93but the performance can be improved with time. The important thing is th=
at <a href=3D"http://www.datastax.com/documentation/articles/cassandra/cass=
andrathenandnow.html">Cassandra is <em>first</em></a> to have a distributed=
 linearizable data store, or something.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>That said, sometimes you really do need linearizable operations. That=E2=
=80=99s why we added lightweight transactions in Cassandra 2.0 This is a si=
gn of Cassandra maturing =E2=80=94 Cassandra 1.0 (released October 2011) wa=
s the fulfilment of its designers original vision; Cassandra 2.0 takes it i=
n new directions to make it even more powerful.</p>
<p>Open source has had the reputation of producing good imitations, but not=
 innovation. Perhaps Cassandra=E2=80=99s origins as a hybrid of Dynamo and =
Bigtable did not disprove this, but Apache Cassandra=E2=80=99s development =
of lightweight transactions and CQL are true industry firsts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The first thing you=E2=80=99ll notice if you try to test the new transac=
tion system is that the Java driver doesn=E2=80=99t support it. It=E2=80=99=
ll throw some weird exceptions like =E2=80=9Cunknown consistency level SERI=
AL=E2=80=9D, because it doesn=E2=80=99t support the v2 native Cassandra pro=
tocol yet. So you=E2=80=99ll need to use the Python Thrift client, or, in m=
y case, get a patched client from DataStax.</p>
<p>The second thing you=E2=80=99ll notice is deadlocks. In my Jepsen tests,=
 the cluster would go unresponsive after the first 10 or so transactions=E2=
=80=93and it would never recover. Any further attempts to modify a cell via=
 transaction would spin endlessly in failed transactions, until I manually =
truncated the system.paxos table.</p>
<p>You can=E2=80=99t make this shit up.</p>
<p>So you confer with DataStax for a while, and they manage to reproduce an=
d fix the bug: <a href=3D"https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-6=
029">#6029</a> (Lightweight transactions race render primary key useless), =
and <a href=3D"https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-5985">#5985<=
/a> (Paxos replay of in progress update is incorrect). You start building p=
atched versions of Cassandra.</p>
<pre><code>git checkout paxos-fixed-hopefully
</code></pre>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s give it a whirl. In <a href=3D"https://github.com/aphyr/je=
psen/blob/master/src/jepsen/cassandra.clj#L228-L290">this transaction test<=
/a>, we perform repeated compare-and-set operations against a single cell, =
retrying failed attempts for up to 10 seconds. The first thing you=E2=80=99=
ll notice is that those four round-trips aren=E2=80=99t exactly lightweight=
, which means that at 50 transactions/sec, the majority of transaction atte=
mpts time out:</p>
<p><img class=3D"attachment pure-img" src=3D"https://aphyr.com/data/posts/2=
94/cassandra-txn-latency.png" alt=3D"cassandra-txn-latency.png" title=3D"ca=
ssandra-txn-latency.png"></p>
<p>But we=E2=80=99re less concerned with performance or availability than <=
em>safety</em>. Let=E2=80=99s slow down the test to 5 transactions/sec to r=
educe contention, and check: are lightweight transactions actually lineariz=
able?</p>
<pre><code>2000 total
829 acknowledged
827 survivors
3 acknowledged writes lost! (=E2=95=AF=C2=B0=E2=96=A1=C2=B0=EF=BC=89=E2=95=
=AF=EF=B8=B5 =E2=94=BB=E2=94=81=E2=94=BB
(102 1628 1988)
1 unacknowledged writes found! =E3=83=BD(=C2=B4=E3=83=BC=EF=BD=80)=E3=83=8E
(283)
0.4145 ack rate
0.0036188178 loss rate
0.0012062726 unacknowledged but successful rate
</code></pre>
<p>No. <b>Cassandra lightweight transactions are not even close to correct.=
</b> Depending on throughput, they may drop anywhere from 1-5% of acknowled=
ged writes=E2=80=93and this doesn=E2=80=99t even require a network partitio=
n to demonstrate. It=E2=80=99s just a broken implementation of Paxos. In ad=
dition to the deadlock bug, these Jepsen tests revealed <a href=3D"https://=
issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-6012">#6012</a> (Cassandra may acce=
pt multiple proposals for a single Paxos round) and <a href=3D"https://issu=
es.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-6013">#6013</a> (unnecessarily high fal=
se negative probabilities).</p>
<p><a href=3D"http://research.google.com/archive/paxos_made_live.pdf">Paxos=
 is notoriously difficult to implement correctly</a>. The Chubby authors no=
te:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Our tests start in safety mode and inject random failures into the syste=
m. After running for a predetermined period of time, we stop injecting fail=
ures and give the system time to fully recover. Then we switch
the test to liveness mode. The purpose for the liveness test is to verify t=
hat the system does not deadlock
after a sequence of failures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p></p><div style=3D"clear: both"></div><p></p>
<blockquote>
<p>This test proved useful in finding various subtle protocol errors, inclu=
ding errors in our group membership
implementation, and our modifications to deal with corrupted disks=E2=80=A6=
. We found additional bugs, some of which took weeks of simulated execution=
 time (at extremely high failure rates) to find.</p>
</blockquote>
<p></p><div style=3D"clear: both"></div><p></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Our hooks can be used to crash a
replica, disconnect it from other replicas for a period of time or force a =
replica to pretend that it is no longer
the master. This test found five subtle bugs in Chubby related to master fa=
ilover in its first two weeks.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And in particular, I want to emphasize:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>By their very nature, fault-tolerant systems try to mask problems. Thus =
they can mask bugs or
configuration problems while insidiously lowering their own fault-tolerance=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The bugs I found were low-hanging fruit: anyone who ran a few hundred si=
mple transactions could reproduce them, even without causing a single node =
or network failure. Why didn=E2=80=99t DataStax catch this in the release p=
rocess? Why publish glowing blog posts and smug retrospectives if the most =
fundamental safety properties of the application haven=E2=80=99t been trivi=
ally verified? And if I hadn=E2=80=99t reported these bugs, how many users =
do you suppose would have been subject to silent data loss or corruption in=
 prod?</p>
<p>I can=E2=80=99t say this strongly enough: One way or another, software i=
s <em>always</em> tested: either by the maintainers, by users, or by applic=
ations in production. One of my goals in this series is to push database ve=
ndors to test their software <em>prior</em> to release, so that we can all =
enjoy safer, faster systems. If you=E2=80=99re writing a database, <em>plea=
se</em> try to verify its correctness experimentally. You don=E2=80=99t nee=
d to do a perfect job=E2=80=93testing is tough!=E2=80=93but a little effort=
 can catch 90% of the bugs.</p>
<h2><a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/294-call-me-maybe-cassandra#final-th=
oughts" id=3D"final-thoughts">Final thoughts</a></h2>
<p>DataStax and the open-source community around Cassandra have been workin=
g hard on the AP storage problem for several years, and it shows. Cassandra=
 runs on thousand-node clusters and accepts phenomenal write volume. It=E2=
=80=99s extraordinarily suited for high-throughput capture of immutable or =
otherwise log-oriented data, and its AAE and tunable durability features wo=
rk well. It is, in short, a capable AP datastore, and though I haven=E2=80=
=99t deployed it personally, many engineers I respect recommend it from the=
ir production experience wholeheartedly.</p>
<p>Jonathan Ellis, Aleksey Yeschenko=E2=80=8E, and Patrick McFadin were all=
 very helpful in helping me understand Cassandra=E2=80=99s model, and I hop=
e that I have depicted it accurately here. Any errors are mine alone. I=E2=
=80=99m especially thankful that they volunteered so much of their time on =
nights and weekends to help someone tear apart their hard work, and that th=
ey=E2=80=99ve fixed the bugs I=E2=80=99ve found so quickly. Reproducing and=
 fixing distributed systems bugs is an especially challenging task, and it =
speaks to the skill of the entire Cassandra team.</p>
<p>DataStax has adapted some of these Jepsen tests for use in their interna=
l testing process, and, like Basho, may use Jepsen directly to help test fu=
ture releases. I=E2=80=99m optimistic that they=E2=80=99ll notify users tha=
t the transactional features are unsafe in the current release, and clarify=
 their documentation and marketing. Again, there=E2=80=99s nothing technica=
lly <em>wrong</em> with many of the behaviors I=E2=80=99ve discussed above=
=E2=80=93they=E2=80=99re simply <em>subtle</em>, and deserve clear expositi=
on so that users can interpret them correctly.</p>
<p>I=E2=80=99m looking forward to watching a good database improve.</p>

    </div>
  </article>
</div>
